<p>Marc Lange, currently professor of philosophy at the <a href="https://philosophy.unc.edu/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill</a>, will be moving to <a href="https://philosophy.rutgers.edu/">Rutgers University</a>.<span id="more-53888"></span></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-53891 aligncenter" src="https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/lange-marc-photo.png" alt="" width="499" height="412" srcset="https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/lange-marc-photo.png 953w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/lange-marc-photo-300x248.png 300w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/lange-marc-photo-768x634.png 768w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/lange-marc-photo-400x330.png 400w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 499px) 100vw, 499px" /></p>
<p>Professor Lange works in philosophy of science and related areas of metaphysics and epistemology, including parts of the philosophy of physics, philosophy of biology, and philosophy of mathematics. He is the author of, among things, <em>Because Without Cause: Non-Causal Explanations in Science and Mathematics </em>(2016), <em>Laws and Lawmakers: Science, Metaphysics, and the Laws of Nature </em>(2009), and <em>Natural Laws in Scientific Practice </em>(2000). You can learn more about his research <a href="https://philosophy.unc.edu/people/marc-lange/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">here</a> and <a href="https://philpeople.org/profiles/marc-lange" target="_blank" rel="noopener">here</a>.</p>
<p>He takes up his new position as professor of philosophy at Rutgers this coming fall.</p>
<p>(via Dean Zimmerman)</p><p>The post <a href="https://dailynous.com/2025/05/19/lange-from-unc-to-rutgers/">Lange from UNC to Rutgers</a> first appeared on <a href="https://dailynous.com">Daily Nous</a>.</p>